body:
Based on #4249 I was under the impression that by setting the top name argument of my verilated file to "", I would get a VCD file where my verilog top module is the top of the verilog file. However, it seems like this only works if the verilog module has no arguments

With
```verilog
module main(input x);
    reg val = 0;

    initial begin
       $dumpfile("out.vcd");
       $dumpvars(0, main);

       $finish();
    end
endmodule
```
A main.cpp with
```cpp
// Verilated -*- C++ -*-
// DESCRIPTION: main() calling loop, created with Verilator --main

#include "verilated.h"
#include "Vmain.h"

//======================

int main(int argc, char** argv, char**) {
    // Setup context, defaults, and parse command line
    Verilated::debug(0);
    const std::unique_ptr<VerilatedContext> contextp{new VerilatedContext};
    contextp->traceEverOn(true);
    contextp->commandArgs(argc, argv);

    // Construct the Verilated model, from Vtop.h generated from Verilating
    const std::unique_ptr<Vmain> topp{new Vmain{contextp.get(), ""}}; // *NOTE* Setting top to "" here

    // Simulate until $finish
    for(int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        // Evaluate model
        topp->eval();
        // Advance time
        contextp->timeInc(1);
    }

    if (!contextp->gotFinish()) {
        VL_DEBUG_IF(VL_PRINTF("+ Exiting without $finish; no events left\n"););
    }

    // Final model cleanup
    topp->final();
    return 0;
}
```
when compiled with
```bash
verilator" "--cc" "--exe" "--build" --top-module main "-Wno-fatal" "--trace" main.v main.cpp
```

The vcd file ends up with a scope called `top` in which my actual top `main` is located
![image](https://github.com/verilator/verilator/assets/5312813/179f8aac-bb14-42fd-8540-2e3f958b2535)


Removing the input `input x`, thus making the verilog
```verilog
module main(input x);
    reg val = 0;

    initial begin
       $dumpfile("out.vcd");
       $dumpvars(0, main);

       $finish();
    end
endmodule
```

Gives the expected result

I need this for similar reasons as #4249. I want the vcd files coming out of verilator to have a similar structure to my test benches in cocotb in which my top verilog module is the top module.

Edit: This is on `Verilator 5.012 2023-06-13 rev UNKNOWN.REV`
